                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d258">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.801 Search/34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-11-14T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 14, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>394. Your 978, November 12, 1 p.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d258fn15">Not
                        printed.</note> The Department prefers to withhold comment on the proposed
                    procedure for the stopping and searching of vessels until it has received text
                    of note from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs with enclosures. Pending the
                    receipt of the Department’s further instructions,<note n="16" xml:id="d258fn16"
                        >No. 381, dated January 26, 1931.</note> the Legation may, if circumstances
                    warrant, inform the Chinese authorities that the Legation makes full reservation
                    of rights granted to American citizens and shipping under the treaties. Inform
                    the Department promptly of any action taken in connection with American vessels
                    under the new instructions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
